<styl>by <m2>By <m0>GREGG FIELDS<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Business Writer<ql>
<m1><styl>capline,4<ql>
<m2><ql>
<ql>
<m0>W<m2><ql>
<m0>hen a game called Big Business collides with a business called Big Sports, the most obvious common denominator is Big Money.<ep>
  Teams collect it, players earn it and companies pay it, in the form of advertising and skybox sales.<ep>
  With South Florida set to multiply its indoor sports arenas by three (--) the original Miami Arena being joined by two new brethren (--) the question that marketers, sports economists and corporate budgetmeisters are asking is this:<ep>
  Is there going to be enough money to go around?<ep>
  ``It's a great question,'' said Doug Logan, commissioner of Major League Soccer and a well-known sports business consultant. ``You take a city like Miami, which doesn't have an overabundance of Fortune 500 companies, and it almost dictates choosing one over another. The war among facilities is going to be unbelievable.''<ep>
  It's a question being debated around the country, with virtually every major city, it seems, either unveiling or planning a new sports arena.<ep>
  The issue has particular relevance here because of the intertwining financial interest of companies, teams and public money. Also, South Florida is going against the grain (--) most communities, even much larger ones, have decided that economics mandate a two-team arena.<ep>
  The importance of economics is undeniable. Although precise details haven't been worked out, Broward estimates skybox and club seating would generate more than $15 million in revenues. Of that, approximately 51 luxury suites would generate $3.4 million in revenue, suggesting an average price of about $66,000 annually. The other $12 million would come from club seating, which isn't in a box but carries privileges such as preferred parking and advantageous floor position.<ep>
  In a typical entertainment venture, of course, investors risk their capital and take losses if it fails. In South Florida, however, the taxpayers are most at risk should the arenas founder. And in the case of the proposed arena for downtown Miami, the facility is scheduled to be built on a valuable community resource (--) downtown waterfront property.<ep>
  Central to the economic success will be the in-arena advertising and the sale of skyboxes to well-heeled patrons, most likely corporations and professional organizations such as law firms.<ep>
  But it won't be an easy sell. In the years since the Miami Arena's plans were first unveiled, the number of local companies that have folded or been merged out of existence include Eastern Airlines, AmeriFirst Bank, Pan Am, Southeast Bank, General Development Corp., CenTrust, International Medical Centers and Key Pharmaceuticals.<ep>
  The arena's 18 skyboxes have never sold out (--) the price of them is estimated at $75,000 to $100,000 annually (--) although poor design obviously played a role in that. Still, Joe Robbie Stadium, uniquely posi<m2><ql>
<ql>
